            <h2>NASA's Foundation</h2>
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-lg-4">
                    <img src="~/Images/DwightDEisenhower.jpg" style="border-radius: 50%; height: 300px; width: 300px;" />
                </div>
                <div class="col-lg-8">
                    <p class="info-par">
                        Although NASA's exact founding date is attributed to July 29th, 1958 it's true roots can be traced further. Before NASA, there was NACA (National Advisory Committee
                        for Aeronautics) which was as the name implies, only focused on Aeronautics. On October 4th, 1957, the Russian artificial satellite, Sputnik 1 was launched into Earth's
                        orbit. This event would be known as "The Sputnik Crisis" in the United States and sparked immediate action for the United States to reinforce their own space efforts.
                    </p>
                    <p class="info-par">
                        On January 14th, 1958, NACA's director organized a "Special committee on Space Technology". This committee would bring about a new federal agency that would handle all
                        non military applications of space activity. On July 29th, 1958, NASA officially came to life when acting president Dwight D. Eisenhower (pictured left) signed the
                        "National Aeronautics and Space Act" officially establishing NASA. NASA would begin its operations on October 1st, 1958, completely absorbing the NACA and it's 8,000
                        employees, three major research labratories and two small testing facilities.
                        [<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NASA#Creation">REF</a>]
                    </p>
                </div>
                <br>
            </div>
            <br />
            <h2>NASA's Current Administration</h2>
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-lg-8">
                    <p class="info-par">
                        As NASA is a federal agency, the administrator more often than not is appointed by the current acting president and is confirmed by the U.S. Senate. The current
                        acting administrator is James Frederick "Jim" Bridenstine (pictured right) who was nominated by the United States 45th president Donald J. Trump. Jim Bridenstine
                        was sworn in as NASA's 13th administrator on April 23rd, 2018.
                    </p>
                    <p class="info-par">
                        Bridenstine was elected in 2012 to represent Oklahoma's First Congressional District in the U.S.
                        House of Representatives. He Served on the Armed Services Committee and the Science, Space and Technology Committee. After performing his service in the U.S. Navy,
                        Bridenstine returned to Oklahoma where he would become the Executive Director of Tulsa Air and Space Museum & Planetarium.
                        [<a href="https://www.nasa.gov/nasa-leadership">REF</a>]
                    </p>
                </div>
